"Irvine P.J., Ridgwell A., Lunt D.J.","Assessing the regional disparities in geoengineering impacts",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","18", L18702,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL044447,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77957553228&partnerID=40&md5=885bd26cdc383a0948c880bc77200191","Bristol Research Initiative for the Dynamic Global Environment, School of Geographical Sciences, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1SS, United Kingdom; British Antarctic Survey, Cambridge, United Kingdom","Irvine, P.J., Bristol Research Initiative for the Dynamic Global Environment, School of Geographical Sciences, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1SS, United Kingdom; Ridgwell, A., Bristol Research Initiative for the Dynamic Global Environment, School of Geographical Sciences, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1SS, United Kingdom; Lunt, D.J., Bristol Research Initiative for the Dynamic Global Environment, School of Geographical Sciences, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1SS, United Kingdom, British Antarctic Survey, Cambridge, United Kingdom","Solar Radiation Management (SRM) Geoengineering may ameliorate many consequences of global warming but also has the potential to drive regional climates outside the envelope of greenhouse-gas induced warming, creating novel conditions, and could affect precipitation in some regions disproportionably. Here, using a fully coupled climate model we explore some new methodologies for assessing regional disparities in geoengineering impacts. Taking a 4 × CO<inf>2</inf> climate and an idealized sunshade SRM strategy, we consider different fractions of the maximum theoretical, 4 × CO<inf>2</inf>- cancelling global mean cooling. Whilst regional predictions in particularly relatively low resolution global climate models must be treated with caution, our simulations indicate that it might be possible to identify a level of SRM geoengineering capable of meeting multiple targets, such as maintaining a stable mass balance of the Greenland ice sheet and cooling global climate, but without reducing global precipitation below pre-industrial or exposing significant fractions of the Earth to novel climate conditions. Copyright © 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Computer simulation; Earth (planet); Glacial geology; Global warming; Sun; Climate condition; Fully-coupled; Geoengineering; Global climate model; Global climates; Global precipitation; Greenland Ice Sheet; Low resolution; Mass balance; Mean cooling; Multiple targets; Pre-industrial; Radiation management; Regional climate; Regional disparities; Climate models; assessment method; carbon dioxide; climate conditions; climate modeling; cooling; engineering geology; global warming; greenhouse gas; numerical model; precipitation (climatology); regional climate; remediation; resolution; solar radiation; Arctic; Greenland",,,,,,"Angel, R., Feasibility of cooling the Earth with a cloud of small spacecraft near the inner Langrange point (L1) (2006) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 103 (46), pp. 17184-17189. , DOI 10.1073/pnas.0608163103; Anthoff, D., Hepburn, C., Tol, R.S.J., Equity weighting and the marginal damage costs of climate change (2009) Ecol. Econ., 68 (3), pp. 836-849. , doi:10.1016/j.ecolecon.2008.06.017; Bala, G., Duffy, P.B., Taylor, K.E., Impact of geoengineering schemes on the global hydrological cycle (2008) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 105 (22), pp. 7664-7669. , http://www.pnas.org/cgi/reprint/105/22/7664, DOI 10.1073/pnas.0711648105; Brovkin, V., Petoukhov, V., Claussen, M., Bauer, E., Archer, D., Jaeger, C., Geoengineering climate by stratospheric sulfur injections: Earth system vulnerability to technological failure (2009) Clim. Change, 92 (3-4), pp. 243-259. , doi:10.1007/s10584-008-9490-1; Cox, P.M., Betts, R.A., Jones, C.D., Spall, S.A., Totterdell, I.J., Acceleration of global warming due to carbon-cycle feedbacks in a coupled climate model (2000) Nature, 408 (6809), pp. 184-187. , doi:10.1038/35041539; Crutzen, P.J., Albedo enhancement by stratospheric sulfur injections: A contribution to resolve a policy dilemma? (2006) Climatic Change, 77 (3-4), pp. 211-219. , DOI 10.1007/s10584-006-9101-y; Govindasamy, B., Caldeira, K., Duffy, P.B., Geoengineering Earths radiation balance to mitigate climate change from a quadrupling of CO2 (2003) Global Planet. Change, 37 (1-2), pp. 157-168. , doi:10.1016/S0921- 8181(02); Hansen, J., Sato, M., Ruedy, R., Lo, K., Lea, D.W., Medina-Elizade, M., Global temperature change (2006) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 103 (39), pp. 14288-14293. , DOI 10.1073/pnas.0606291103; (2007) Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis: Contribution of Working Group 1 to the Fourth Assesment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, p. 996. , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) edited by S. Solomon et al. Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Irvine, P.J., Lunt, D.J., Stone, E.J., Ridgwell, A., The fate of the Greenland Ice Sheet in a geoengineered, high CO2 world (2009) Environ. Res. Lett., 4 (4), p. 045109. , doi:10.1088/1748-9326/4/4/045109; (2007) Global Population Database, , http://www.ornl.gov/sci/landscan, LandScan Oak Ridge Natl. Lab., Oak Ridge, Tenn; Lenton, T.M., Vaughan, N.E., The radiative forcing potential of different climate geoengineering options (2009) Atmos. Chem. Phys., 9 (15), pp. 5539-5561. , doi:10.5194/acp-9-5539-2009; Lenton, T.M., Held, H., Kriegler, E., Hall, J.W., Lucht, W., Rahmstorf, S., Schellnhuber, H.J., Tipping elements in the Earth's climate system (2008) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 105 (6), pp. 1786-1793. , http://www.pnas.org/cgi/reprint/105/6/1786, DOI 10.1073/pnas.0705414105; Lunt, D.J., Ross, I., Hopley, P.J., Valdes, P.J., Modelling Late Oligocene C<inf>4</inf> grasses and climate (2007) Palaeogeography,